In the fourth and final season of this comedy-drama, Hannah Baxter (Bille Piper) reluctantly takes over the role of madame when Stephanie (Cherie Lunghi) is arrested for money laundering. She is also in charge of Stephanie's daughter Poppy (Lily James) who is unaware of the career choice both her mother and Hannah have made. In addition, Hannah's double life is made more complicated when she and Ben become more than just friends.

Beautiful and smart Hannah Baxter (Billie Piper) continues leading her double life as glamorous call girl Belle de Jour in the third season of this comedy-drama. She has a falling out with her best friend Ben (Iddo Goldberg) when he objects to her relationship with Duncan (James D'Arcy), the publisher of her book. Also, Bambi (Ashley Madekwe), a naïve wannabe escort, ignores the advice of her madame, Stephanie (Cherie Lunghi), about romantic entanglements and falls in love with her eccentric client Byron (David Dawson).

Season 2 continues to follow the sexploits of London call girl, Hannah Baxter (Billie Piper). She struggles to give up her life as Belle de Jour when she begins a real relationship with Dr. Alex McLoud (Callum Blue). In addition, being an escort may not be as glamorous as it seems when the issue of rape within prostitution is explored.

Season 1 of this comedy-drama examines the sexploits of a highly educated, high-priced London escort. Her professional name is Belle de Jour (Billie Piper) but when she is not working as a call girl she is known simply as Hannah Baxter. She is an expert at leading a double life but trouble ensues when her two lives collide. Ben (Iddo Goldberg) is her best friend and ex-boyfriend. He knows about Hannah's secret and it is a constant cause of friction between them.

Season 2 of the comedy series tackles issues that are at the forefront of present-day America. Alex (Marcel Ruiz) is taunted at school with "build the wall"; Lydia (Rita Moreno) has to take her citizenship test, which she finds very difficult and might result in her being deported; Penelope (Justina Machado) recalls how 9/11 changed her life and forced her to make decisions that ultimately caused her struggles with mental illness. However, not everything is dark and gloomy: This season also deals with Elena's (Isabella Gomez) love life, Dwayne's (Todd Grinnell) unwavering support of the family, and a new boyfriend for Penelope.

This comedy series is based on a sitcom of the same name that ran from 1975 to 1984, and follows the life of a Cuban-American family. Penelope (Justina Machado) is a nurse in the Army dealing with depression and anxiety after returning from service; Dwayne (Todd Grinnell) is Penelope's best friend, her landlord and a womanizer; Elena (Isabella Gomez) is Penelope's teenage daughter, who's dealing with personal issues that might affect her relationship with her family; Alex (Marcel Ruiz) is Penelope's son, who's trying to be popular at school; Lydia (Rita Moreno) is Penelope's very traditional Cuban mother. In Season 1, the family go through changes and difficult times, and deal with issues such as PTSD, depression and relationship drama.
